<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911218-0024</DOCNO><DOCID>911218-0024.</DOCID><HL>   Mrs. Bush to Make Filing   For New Hampshire Race</HL><DATE>12/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16</SO><NS>POLITICS (PLT)</NS><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><RE>NEW HAMPSHIRE (NH)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- First lady Barbara Bush will travel to NewHampshire today to file documents enabling President Bush tocompete in that state's Feb. 18 presidential primary, thefirst in the nation.   Mrs. Bush will pay the $1,000 campaign filing fee and havelunch while in New Hampshire, officials said.</LP><TEXT>   Although Mr. Bush has yet to formally declare his campaignfor re-election, and his aides insist he isn't yet acandidate, he has raised about $2.1 million for a campaignand has unveiled his campaign leadership team. He has alsoqualified for the South Dakota Republican primary, to be heldFeb. 25.   The president has been delaying a formal announcement,preferring to take advantage of the stature of incumbency andto urge opponents to delay their political attacks and focuson the nation's economic problems. Campaign officials havesaid he is likely to delay his formal announcement untilafter his Jan. 28 State of the Union address.   Mr. Bush's campaign team, however, is proceeding withplans to hire additional staff. This week, officialsinterviewed candidates for the post of campaign presssecretary, including White House deputy press secretary JudySmith and former Republican National Committee spokesmanLeslie Goodman.   In the New Hampshire primary, Mr. Bush will face PatrickBuchanan, a television commentator and former Reaganadministration official.</TEXT></DOC>